                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.74/238: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-05-12T16:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 12, 1922—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 12—8:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>216. Department’s 114, May 8. Following is summary of oral communication which I
                    received today from the Ministry of Communications.</p>
                <p>There recently called at the Ministry of Communications a representative of
                    British, French, and Japanese wireless interests. He stated that these interests
                    would soon present to the Chinese Government an agreement which they had reached
                    on wireless policy in China. The Ministry received the impression that this
                    policy was at variance with that of the Washington Conference. The Federal
                    Telegraph contract continues to be decried by these wireless interests who
                    declare that it can not be put into execution. Because of the long delay by the
                    Federal Telegraph Company the Ministry of Communications is unable to disprove
                    this. Is it not possible for the Federal Company to hasten? The Ministry is
                    becoming anxious.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
